06097nam a22008895i 9781575066929DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750669297 a10.1515/97815750669292doi  a(DE-B1597)584144  a(OCoLC)1266229177  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a223/.80604aThe Words of the Wise Are like Goads :bEngaging Qohelet in the 21st Century /ced. by Mark J. Boda, Cristian Rata, Tremper Longman III. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (528 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"Meaningless, meaningless, everything is meaningless." The word "meaningless" (hebel) appears more than 40 times in the book of Ecclesiastes and raises the question why a book that appears to deny meaning or purpose is included in the Bible. Many questions of interpretation as well as relevance surround the book of Ecclesiastes, including indeed the proper translation and understanding of the word hebel. If, after all, the book does examine the question of the meaning of life, what could be more important?The present volume explores Ecclesiastes/Qohelet on many different levels: linguistic, text-critical, theological, historical, and literary. The contributors, chosen from many of the leading and emerging experts on the book, present both the state of the field and their own assessment of the varied interpretive issues of Ecclesiastes. They include scholars, preachers, and philosophers. It should be helpful not only to scholars but also to all who want to study this book seriously.The first section of this volume deals with the history of interpretation. The second section is concerned with issues of history, form, and rhetoric. Section three is about key concepts and passages. The fourth section focuses on the language and grammar of Qohelet. The last section engages practical issues of interpretation. The volume is designed to provide exposure to a variety of readers who seek to engage Qohelet in fresh ways in the twenty-first century-from historians of interpretation to biblical exegetes to linguists to theological students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aBartholomew, Craig G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeldman, David J. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoda, Mark J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoda, Mark J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristianson, Eric S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempster, Stephen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFredericks, Daniel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHobbins, John F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmstedt, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngram, Doug, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeithart, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongman III, Tremper, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLongman, Tremper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeek, Russell L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMroczek, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Dowd, Ryan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/